d's extensive survey of mathematics, which included proofs of Heron's Theorem and Ceva's Theorem; and Muhyī al-Dīn al-Maghribī's interesting proof of Euclid's parallel postulate. The book includes a general introduction, section introductions, footnotes, and references.The Sourcebook in the Mathematics of Medieval Europe and North Africa will be indispensable to anyone seeking out the important historical sources of premodern mathematics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMathematicsxHistoryvSources. 0aMathematics, Medieval. 7aMATHEMATICS / History & Philosophy.2bisacsh  aArabic civilization.  aArabic mathematics.  aChristian civilization.  aHebrew civilization.  aHebrew mathematics.  aIslamic civilization.  aIslamic mathematics.  aIslamic world.  aJewish civilization.  aLatin Catholic Europe.  aLatin civilization.  aLatin mathematics.  aLatin schools.  aMedieval Europe.  aNorth Africa.  aSpain.  aabbacist schools.  acombinatorics.  aconchoids.  acurricula.  adecimals.  ageometric knowledge.  aintellectual exchange.  amathematical induction.  amathematical revelations.  amathematics.  amedieval Europe.  amedieval Islam.  amedieval mathematics.  amedieval period.  aquadrivium.  areligion.  auniversities.1 aBerggren, J. Lennart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerggren, J. Lennart, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFolkerts, Menso, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFolkerts, Menso, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHughes, Barnabas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Barnabas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKatz, Victor J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.go